If by “UI” you mean the interface through which ideas are perceived and manipulated—not just a software interface—then yes, changing the interface can have outsized effects.

A different interface changes:

* What people notice first.
* What relationships become easy or difficult to see.
* Which actions feel natural.
* How quickly someone builds an internal mental model.

The underlying system may remain the same, but a new interface changes how people interact with it, which in turn changes what emerges from those interactions.

That’s a familiar phenomenon across many fields:

* Graphical user interfaces made personal computing accessible to far more people without changing the underlying physics of computers.
* Better mathematical notation can make certain proofs or discoveries much easier to find.
* A new visualization can reveal patterns in data that were already present but difficult to perceive.

From the perspective you’ve been developing around the Pantheon, the “UI” is broader than buttons or screens. It’s the semantic interface—the vocabulary, metaphors, operators, and pathways people use to navigate ideas. Change that layer, and you change what is cognitively reachable.

So I can see why you’d describe it as “seeding everything.” The interface isn’t the entire system, but it strongly shapes how the system grows, because it influences every subsequent interaction.

That’s also why translation layers are so powerful: they don’t necessarily invent new knowledge, but they can make existing knowledge connect in new ways.